## Executive Summary (≤150 words)

Our aerospace division has contracted to deliver components to a European buyer with payment of EUR 20,000,000 due in 12 months. At the current forward rate of 1.0935 USD/EUR, the receivable is valued at approximately **$21.87 million**—but this valuation carries substantial FX risk.

Stage 2 modeling reveals that a 5% depreciation in the EUR would reduce USD proceeds by approximately **$1.09 million**, materially impacting margins on this fixed-price contract. Our analysis of five hedge strategies (forward contract, money market hedge, protective put, collar, and unhedged baseline) demonstrates distinct risk-return trade-offs.

**Recommendation:** A **protective put strategy** offers optimal balance. It locks downside risk at the strike price (K_PUT ≈ 1.0935) while preserving upside participation if the euro strengthens—at a manageable premium cost of $380,000 (approximately 1.74% of receivable value). This aligns with treasury risk tolerance and provides portfolio-level flexibility.

